english:
  title: Preface to the Commentary on the Vajra Samadhi Sutra
  author: Wonhyo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The source of the singular mind transcends both being and non-being, dwelling in solitary purity. The ocean of threefold emptiness merges the true and the conventional, resting in luminous clarity. In this clarity that merges the two without becoming one, in this solitary purity that transcends boundaries yet is not the middle—here lies the dharma: possessing nothing, it does not dwell in emptiness; manifesting form, it does not dwell in existence. Merging the two without becoming one, what is not-true does not thereby become conventional, and what is not-conventional does not thereby become true. Merging the two without becoming one, the nature of the conventional establishes all things without exception, and the marks of defilement and purity embrace all possibilities. Transcending boundaries yet not dwelling in the middle, the dharmas of being and non-being create without limitation, and the principles of affirmation and negation pervade all things. Thus there is destruction without what is destroyed, establishment without what is established—we may call this the ultimate truth that transcends logic, the great reality beyond negation.

    This is the profound meaning of this scripture. Because truth transcends affirmation, the language of teaching subtly accords with the turning wheel. Because ultimate truth transcends logic, the doctrine transmitted surpasses all conceptual boundaries. Because nothing remains unbroken, it bears the name Vajra Samadhi. Because nothing fails to be established, it bears the name Sutra of Comprehensive Mahayana. Since all doctrinal meanings do not exceed these two, they also bear the name Doctrine of Limitless Meaning. And lifting a single aspect as its title, it is called the Vajra Samadhi Sutra.
  footnotes:
    - The 'threefold emptiness' (三空) refers to three key Buddhist philosophical concepts concerning the absence of inherent nature.
    - The 'turning wheel' or 'circling hub' (環中) is a metaphor for the dharmic teaching that returns endlessly without fixed center or circumference.
    - '''Beyond the square limits'' (方外) suggests transcendence of conventional spatial and conceptual boundaries.'
